text:
You are the king/queen of your life!
-------------------------------------------
Not the kind of king/queen that fit to what others say and think of how you should be, BUT, your unique way of being you, Free to be and free to act! (this is key!)
-------------------------------------------
Here is what I notice from changing myself so much in the past 5-6 years. People will always have something to say about anything. -------------------------------------------
Basically, from the moment we were born, people were saying things, and then we matured a bit, and people kept saying things, And so on and on until today, people keep saying things!
--------------------------------------------
The truth is, people will never stop saying things, regardless of what you do. --------------------------------------------
You be you and don't let anybody to judge or shame you. I mean, they will keep judging and shaming, and you have nothing to do about it. --------------------------------------------
Be you and don't let it bother you!
--------------------------------------------
That way, you will be able to find your true friends. --------------------------------------------
The rest don't even worth wasting time writing about at all ğŸ˜—. (ğŸ™„)
--------------------------------------------
Well, everyone on their own journey, have compassion for everyone and understand that even people who judge and shame you, might be dealing with stuff. I don't think they mean to do evil; sometimes, we do thing automatically without a real intention to harm others.

I'm 6 ft 3 and as a man I have had privileges due to that my whole life. When I was in grade school and highschool I was skinny and weak the entire time even up until getting my highschool diploma. Look at the contrast between short GUY memes and short GIRL memes. Short guy memes are to emasculate short men whereas short girl memes are ment to empathize with and empower short women. Emasculating men does not empower women (unless they are misandrist).

[Shapes of Freedom, 4/6]
... You visualize yourself in a place where thereâ€™s no should or must, no age, no matter tiding you up.
You concentrate, your mind dances, still lost but more certain each second of the final goal.
â€œWhat did I really want back then ?â€ The answer is hard to find, itâ€™s blown into pieces and spread all over the hidden place. But itâ€™s right there, a bit everywhere.
Three things, three dreams you really wanted to achieve as a child... Their outlines slowly appear to you. You are drawn to them like a pole to its opposite. But once you see their faces, will you find the power to embrace them ? In a poetic way, any change ressembles a death. Without it, a new part of yourself cannot be born. And death in any form is frightening at the very least...
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
Nothing worth doing is *ever* easy.  Yet, for some reason, we can acknowledge the challenges with just about anything in life and still be supported...except for parenting: the hardest/most important job in the world.  There is a lot of support within our village, but we still have a long way to go to get away from the shame game.  The comments section of any parenting page will readily prove this.  I love motherhood.  It is the most incredible journey Iâ€™ve ever been on.  But itâ€™s also the hardest fucking thing Iâ€™ve ever done.  If we didnâ€™t love our kids so much, the reality is, parenting wouldnâ€™t be this hard!  I strive to keep things real and relatable on this page - and thatâ€™s going to include the beautiful, the good, the bad, and the ugly.  There is no shame in feeling overwhelmed and speaking your truth when things are feeling difficult - and donâ€™t ever let anyone tell you otherwise.  You can feel challenged and overwhelmed, and still be incredibly grateful for your children.  The two are not mutually exclusive.

text:
Day 14

Adventure

As you journey through life a day at a time, donâ€™t discount Godâ€™s instructions for your life. â€”
Hi, my name is Valerie, and Iâ€™m a recovering control addict. I believe thereâ€™s a few of you out there, so letâ€™s shift together. Today, right now... letâ€™s take look in the mirror at our body and just for a moment think of itâ€™s physical health as if itâ€™s a vehicle and ask it... what adventures are we going to take and how do I best prepare us for the journey of a lifetime? We are given this gift, our very first gift for a purpose. Quite literally I know people with the fanciest cars out there who donâ€™t take care of them, and conversely people with simple vehicles that are super well loved! When you ask your spirit guide this question, literally everything will begin to shift for you! 
What do we control? Damn near everything! We make ourselves  diabetic and put ourselves in little shitty boxes. Why? Maybe fear? Fear of letting go and exploring? Fear of doing it wrong?  shaming Who knows? Maybe ask yourself, why? 
Letâ€™s wrap this back into a conversation about living your best life and health. I receive divine downloads (you might call them symptoms, nudges, reminders) and I have responded to many of them. In fact, one of the biggest nudge lead me to this career of helping other people listen to their downloads and nudges. High blood pressure and weight have lead me through this new journey. 
Hereâ€™s what I remind myself and what I want you to remember the next time you get a nudge... itâ€™s imperative that you respond IMMEDIATELY (yes, Iâ€™m yelling) to the messaging! Listen when the lights go on and the reminder is simple, like oil, gas or tire rotation. And avoid letting your vehicle sit in your garage, on the side of the road or on a tow truck. As soon as your body says, hey!!! Iâ€™m overwhelmed, over-heating, over-fed & under-nourished... pay attention and do something. 
No matter what, remember obedience and faith is Godâ€™s way to the TOP!

text: Brene Brown Took the world by storm with her Ted talk on shame, obtaining millions of views and selling almost as many copies of her books on her shame research. One of the main takeaways I learned from her content was that all shame is bad. It affects your health, psychology, and so forth. But as I observe experiences from my own life and counterbalance that with evolutionary biology, I believe thatâ€™s oversimplifying things. I have worked in an organization that screw from 30 to 50 people, and in that time, Iâ€™ve observed a few instances where shaming was used to prevent people from doing things that would affect the group, such as leaving food out in the kitchen accidentally. I theorize that shame has been affectively used as a tool for tribes to condition members of the tribe to do things for the benefit of the tribe. Slut shaming may exist because the society didnâ€™t want women to get pregnant before marriage in a time when contraceptives werenâ€™t available, And when society wanted their women to put more thought into who they chose as a partner before consummation. An offshoot of that is slut shaming as a form of female to female competition. The point is that although there are reasons based on evolution that we do things we do, in the modern world, I believe we can achieve the same results with just as much effectiveness without using shame. Some models are outdated and cause more bad side effects than they are worth. Itâ€™s similar to Ego. I thought ego was mostly or all bad until I read the Third door by @alexbanayan and Bruce lee a life, and discovered two successful people Tony Hsieh of Zappos and Bruce Lee who used ego effectively. The difference between shaming you go in this case is that ego has its pros and cons in ancient history and the modern times, whereas shame in the modern times only has cons where as it had pros in tribal times.

Some people may remember this post. Well I just wanted to share that I did it, and some. Last week I officially hit -28 lbs which is actually more than what I set out to do. When I put on that weight, anyone super close to me knew how much it impacted me, I really struggled to even look at myself in the mirror, I had no confidence what so ever. From being a a teenager Iâ€™ve never been â€˜happyâ€™ with my weight. Actually thatâ€™s a lie, I was once happy with my weight but no one else was, in fact my best friends mum said â€œCharlotte you look ill, youâ€™ve lost too muchâ€. Iâ€™d say Iâ€™ve always just looked â€œnormalâ€ to others, apart from the big gain that Iâ€™ve been getting rid of, but my weight is something that is constantly on my mind, every minute of every day. Do I still enjoy a brownie, yes, do I go to the gym, yes. This isnâ€™t an eating disorder, itâ€™s a body image thing. It might not be visible to others at all, but you never know whatâ€™s going on inside someoneâ€™s head. Some people may read this and think what the hell is she on about sheâ€™s never been huge and never been tiny but itâ€™s not about that, itâ€™s about my own self confidence and how I feel in my skin âœŒğŸ» .

I used to sit and paint in my room and cry for a different life. And when I finally had freedom, I was fearless in thinking I could â€œdo anything.â€ Recently I was told, â€œyou are different. And it is off putting to people. Like youâ€™re trying too hard to be different.â€ And all I could try to explain (and to someone I never thought Iâ€™d have to) was that it was just me. Who I am. My genuine self. And while explaining, searching for an approval and a plea of â€œjust love me for thisâ€. Self growth is hard, and remembering your worth is, at times, bittersweet. However, everyday Iâ€™m making steps to get back to my fearless self, whether it is embraced or not . But, I think 17 year old Haelee would be very proud of the â€œdifferentâ€ life she has made.

text:
It's easy to overthink things... Like everything. ğŸ¤£ğŸ¤” I'm noticing this more and more, weirdly the MORE I schedule time to do the things I need to accomplish for launch day ğŸš€

I've employed some basic skills that are so so easy to forget. (I had forgotten them till my coach said, hey remember these things??) 1. Analog calendar.  Writing things by hand on something I can see with my own two eyes and touch with my hands makes a huge difference.

2. Scheduled time for  work (max 3 to 4 hour time slots) for maximum productivity and attentiveness. 
3. Scheduled time for  selfcare! Walks, tea, whatever it is, this helps keep the creative spirit alive and my heart open. Decreases drudgery.

4. Remembering  presence. More than anything, I want to enjoy my work and enjoy this process of creation and the journey toward personal freedom and success.

5. Quit  shaming myself! Actually, presence helps with this a ton, as does sticking to my schedule. I enjoy my break time, because I know when work time comes, I will be there, all the way. Shame does nothing for motivation, it's almost like a motivation-killer, and can become a sad feedback loop if we aren't aware of it. 
For those of you who have a  goal in mind, however small (even if it's just getting to your mat!), try employing these small skills. Enjoy your work, even if it's work! Why are we here, if not to enjoy life?

And also, importantly, don't forget to  juststart. Work in the here and now. Work for you first, then for others. It's a beautiful thing.

Xx

I started wondering how everyone would treat him, and me in return, for him not believing anymore. I had seen how Mormons treated other family members who didn't believe anymore. It was like they were shunned, second class, not worth talking about. They just sort of disappeared. No one asked them why they left. No one asked if they needed any help. It was horrible. It's like Mormons say (though they would never admit this), that they can be friends and care about you, but only if you're Mormon. ***Side note - I saw a member say that once in a fb group - that she wouldn't go looking for friends who weren't Mormon. ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ğŸ˜‘ As I started thinking about this more and more I realized I didn't like the Mormon culture. In fact I hated it. I was surprised at how much hate I had towards it.

Mormons judge you if you're not wearing your garments. They judge you if you're not able to go into the temple. They judge you if you exercise without garments, wear revealing clothing when on vacation or going to a dance. They judge you if you don't go on a mission.

Somehow you're ALWAYS second best if you're not measuring up to their impossible standards. It's a shaming, judgemental nightmare.

text:
â€œFinal lap of this pregnancy and I feel strong, excited, nervous and powerful. Mixed emotions in so much grace.â€ Earlier, Sameera Reddy posted, â€œI embrace my curves, my cheeks, my water retention and my pregnant belly with a smile.â€ A couple of weeks ago, in response to trolls, @reddysameera  posted a beautiful picture of herself in beachwear with the caption, â€œHer soul was too deep to explore by those who always swam in the shallow end. This is my answer to anyone who feels uncomfortable with me enjoying my pregnant belly.â€ Sameera Reddy had been trolled for her weight after her 1st pregnancy weight, and speaks up now in her second, glowing in her late pregnancy. 
Celebrity mom Sameera Reddy had been trolled for putting on a lot of weight after her first pregnancy, at a time when she was feeling low. While she admits that she had body image issues at that time, she is confident and happy during her second, and the trolls can take a hike!

A friend of mine recently gave birth. A couple of months after the delivery, she looks as trim as she did before pregnancy. At a party recently, I overheard some Indian women talking about her. â€œWho would even believe that she was pregnant?â€ they said as they considered their own belly fat and love handles. I felt sad that they felt the need to make that comparison, but I was not surprised. Arenâ€™t such conversations all too common in India, where a womanâ€™s body is constantly looked at, judged and talked about? 
No wonder that women feel ashamed of and unhappy about their bodies â€“bodies that have survived bringing brand new, beautiful human beings onto this planet; bodies that they should be proud of.

A glowing  SameeraReddy celebrating her second pregnancy
Which is why the positivity that emanates from Sameera Reddyâ€™s social media posts about her pregnancy is refreshing. She is glowing, and why not? The actress is pregnant with her second child, and she has been sharing the most gorgeous pictures of her baby bump, and she has been open and honest about her thoughts and feelings about the same.

text:
Whether it is about how we look, what community we belong to, our lifestyle choices â€“ weâ€™ve been told that we are not good enough. 
When weâ€™re constantly told, we often believe. We tell ourselves that we really arenâ€™t good enough to fit in or that we canâ€™t pull off what weâ€™re set to do. But tell me, is this who you were supposed to be? Does that tag really define you? Is it what makes you who you are?

Meet a boy who suffered from anorexia and found inspiration in Spiderman, a girl who found her voice amidst the everyday crass chatter, a Muslim rapper who broke through the stereotype of his community and a rebel artist who bared her soul to her art.

Here it is â€“ a series of conversations which bring to the table a much needed discussion. It also tells us volumes of how we see people and immediately, even without a second thought, often judge them, unknowingly. 
Itâ€™s important we talk about this, call it out in the open and rip it from itâ€™s very roots, because otherwise, weâ€™ll always believe that weâ€™re not good enough.

text: Found: November 23rd, 2018 - Found q few hours after my previous post.

Today something sad happened that I decided to put into words. My parents finally moved back to Germany and I am as much happy they are back, as I am afraid of old habits and unpleasant moments. Today, two days after theyâ€™ve been back, we decided to go for a swim. I hate going to swim or be by the lake since I was younger, one of the reason being that no matter what age, Iâ€™ve always been told that i should lose weight or simply â€œyou donâ€™t look goodâ€. To be clear, I was not afraid it â€œcouldâ€ happen, it simple always did. .
When I started living alone in Berlin I realized that I started to like myself. Now, weighing +20kg, even more. I used to think it was me becoming strong on my own, also because after several years Iâ€™ve found a partner that loves me the way I am ğŸ–¤ and all that is true, but I also came to realize that most of it came from being literary apart from the comments and pain that make me feel that way to beginn with. .
Today we wanted to swim and after long inner thought, especially the fear of comments from my mom, I decided to not care and simply join. When I finally had my swimsuit on, my mother looked at me and says â€œyou look horrible, especially your hairâ€. Silence. I turned around and said I wonâ€™t join, and she simply replied with okay, bye.

I donâ€™t care if a stranger thinks my legs are big or my head is too bald. But I do care if love ones do. It makes me wonder whatâ€™s going through their mind. Do they think this wonâ€™t hurt, or that it should?
I know I am a strong person, capable of loving myself, able to not care what others say, but I am disappointed, exhausted and deeply sad to be told to not be allowed to like myself the way I am. To not define beauty the way I want to or at least to let me be, especially when itâ€™s so hot outside. 
In the end I stayed home in pain and decided to create this instead. I feel better now. There is so much more to tell and I will sometime, in hopes to make others feel less alone with issues like these â™¥ï¸ .
.

text:
Something I've learned lately.
Quite simple but with  profound implications.

I grew up  privileged and didn't really need to have a job. Honestly I can't say that was the best for my spiritual and practical development. I always got to do what I wanted and as an entrepreneur I did many things. But when I tried to learn the  discipline it would take to do things I didn't want to do, or take my work to the next level, I failed myself over and over. I had gotten used to  shaming myself for not being able to get everything done. There was something wrong with me, why wasn't I able to do more with my  privilege? Why wasn't I living up to my  potential?

I finally realized....how in the heck I was I supposed to learn to do this for myself when I had never really had to be  accountable to anyone else?
So, I stopped shaming myself for needing  accountability, and realized that most everybody does.  Discipline is not easy for many of us.
Especially Someone like me who has multiple interests and  talents, and what I like to call  creative ADD. ğŸ˜‚

I Knew I needed to learn to work and be in a schedule. So I got a full-time  job for the first time ever and I'm learning that now...in my 40s. 
Things have turned around quickly In a relatively short time. 
It's never too late to  reinvent yourself and do work that fulfills you.

New post! -  https://kellybwarner.com/2018/10/25/a-gift-from-the-universe/

A gift from the universe - â€œ'Shame is a controlling device. Shaming someone is an attempt to prevent the person from behaving in a way that embarrasses us'... ...But today she was grabby, even the baby was protesting. I asked for space, she followed me into my room. So I got angry, and she got sad. This is our routine with disagreements. And when I talk to her, I talk about how important it is to not hurt other people, theyâ€™ll feel upset or angry. Why do I do it this way? Because my belief is that itâ€™s ineffective when I say I am hurt or angry based on how sheâ€™s responded in the past. So I instead use this version. I use shame. â€œIf you keep doing it, others wonâ€™t like you.

And, I use this tactic often. It stops the behavior. But, by full admittance, only for a short moment. As parents, sometimes we just need that moment. We live moment to moment. And then, I in turn, shame myself for how I parent in this moments. I carry the weight of all of these mistakes and use them against myself all too often."  juliecameron

text:
Book Review: Jon Ronson - â€˜So Youâ€™ve Been Publicly Shamed'

A recurring theme in my reading after tackling The Scarlet Letter last year, this is my first Ronson book and probably wonâ€™t be my last. Though his blurring between serious journalistic enquiry and Vice-tier all-about-the-author-core can be frustrating, itâ€™s an enjoyable read and brings to light an issue I think many of us need to think about more. If anything, the biggest takeaway has been that my avoidance of twitter is definitely the right call, and I now will avoid that hole like the plague, as it almost seems to congregate all the character traits I dislike the most in people.

Ronson has a generally interesting fascination in the interactions of people that I share, and presents his ideas in an easy to digest manner, but his desire to be impartial leaves the book without much of a conclusion. Itâ€™s really just a series of observations, and in a way that makes it better - he allows us to make up our own minds. A good read, and Iâ€™m glad I picked it up because it is hotly relevant to some of my own work. Iâ€™ve had Ronsonâ€™s The Psychopath Test recommended to me now and Iâ€™m sure Iâ€™ll get to that soon enough.

Year: 2015
Publisher: Pan Macmillan
Genres: non-fiction, pop sociology
Read from: 5th May-20th June 2019

Up next: replacing this as my non-fiction reading will be â€œComing Back to Meâ€ by Marcus Trescothick

text:
THOUGHTS ARE NOT TRUTH - mindfulness is always important but I think itâ€™s most important when it comes to the process of turning our thoughts into our words and express ourselves. â€”
As l wrote the other day â€œwhat happens to a thought when you donâ€™t think itâ€, remember the nugget l took away from the meditation?, and this is in the same line. 
A thought is not you. 
Its not even an expression of you.
A thought is just a thought. â€”
But that does not mean that a thought does not shape you, because it does! 
And if you express a thought that is not aligned with your souls purpose you are on a discourse that might end up being really difficult to stear back home from. 
If you turn a thought into speech that is not truly an expression of you, those words have now affected others and their perception of you.â€¨They will now meet you with the foundation of your words and not who you really are.
This is where bridges are burned.
This is where wars are started.
â€”
So what to do?
Well, we end up where l always end up.
If you have thoughts that are not compassionate and out of loving kindness they are not truth. 
At all!
They are a blip. 
They are expressions of fear, anger, guilt or shame and they are using diversions as blaming, shaming and complaining.
They are not you.

They have gifts to you because you can find out where they come from, why you think they are true, but please dont make them true. 
Remember; â€œwhat happens to a thought when you dont think itâ€â€¦ Let go of it.. Meditate on it

Get back to compassion and loving kindness and find yourself there. â€¦ and then speakâ€¦

momshaming and  parentshaming is a big problem. It effects the parents ability to parent appropriately and therefore can be detrimental to their child(ren)

Iâ€™ve had my fair share of being mom shamed. Iâ€™ve had an older lady make a nasty comment about how she didnâ€™t know which was more annoying my older sons obnoxious singing or my youngest crying. Granted they were both being really loud and I was trying my best to get them under control but that was not helpful for her to say that. It stressed me out and hindered my ability to parent my children

On the other side of the coin there is  momguilt which is just self-shaming. Iâ€™m sure we all have felt this at some point or another because we didnâ€™t feel up to par in our parenting. But you need to remind yourself and each other that we are doing an AMAZING job! Parenting is tough and we donâ€™t need to shame each other nor ourselves. Itâ€™s important that we have confidence in our parenting skills and shaming strips us of that confidence

I talk about another one of my experiences with mom shame as well as why itâ€™s so detrimental in my New â€œSweetâ€  blogpost link in profile.

text:
So Iâ€™m working with the idea of  shame and  guilt as vicarious emotional currencies, meaning energies we can tap and use to get the natural beneficiaries of violence (the partners, the adult children, the generations removed descendants of colonial invaders or murderous police lieutenants) to provide financial  reparations to survivors of violence. 
Now Iâ€™m thinking about it from the lens of my life. My former partner is a sexual predator. His company, Google, is protecting him and has refused to return my hacked documents that implicate him in rape by fraud and proxy. 
Hiring a lawyer isnâ€™t an option. Iâ€™ve had three, and the whole experience was a farce of justice. Plus, after years of hacks and stints in safe houses, the case is now federal, and I live in the worldâ€™s oldest colony,  BorikÃ©n, and work for  PrisonAbolition. 
Complications.  ComplexTrauma too! Thatâ€™s just basic context. 
So, about  PublicShaming as a vicarious emotional currency. Do I name him â€” and the members of his family? Heâ€™s the child of two PhDâ€™s while Iâ€™m the only child of a single mother who raised me on welfare and a missing father often homeless or incarcerated. Do I name his siblings, his colleagues, his friends? 
What happens when shame is mobilized,  monetized, and marketed by survivors â€” me and  MeToo? I get chills at the thought. 
I mean, in a sense Iâ€™m engaging in public  shaming by writing these comments. But shame isnâ€™t financial security for someone who has survived structural violence and still struggles with it. It certainly doesnâ€™t alleviate my concern for other victims. It doesnâ€™t much change the digital landscape. Or does it?  NiUnaMenos. 
And what about  compassion, and  forgiveness? What about  grace and  mercy? Or  RadicalSelfLove? Speaking of which, I need a  cocktail Iâ€™m so stressed over these queries.

text:
Another woman told me emphatically that I wasn't that pretty. She went into detail about brown eyes vs blue, etc.

Why? Women, can we call each other beautiful? This is me after my tearful reaction to her words.

I may not fit into society's conditioned standards of conventional beauty. If we lived in ancient Mayan times our standards of beauty would be flat, sloped foreheads, and big noses.

Whether we fit into a standard or not, can we at least be kind to one another--and ourselves? Can we recognize each of our unique beauty out of society's perspective of perfection?

text:
â€¢Body shaming, read belowâ€¢

The media fuels body shaming, it occurs daily under categories completely unrelated to diet like â€˜celebrity gossipâ€™ or so called â€˜journalismâ€™. What makes body shaming readable material is beyond me. 
The media grasp at anything for financial success and higher ratings; they catch the latest celebrity bloated and suddenly its pregnancy news, what dignity do they have?

We absorb this. Young children absorb this. They including ourselves begin to view this behaviour as a norm and as expected. And thatâ€™s when we compare.

Subconsciously or consciously we objectify ourselves and put ourselves through scrutiny just to fit that â€˜mouldâ€™ the media has repeatedly taught us. 
What frustrates me is that people donâ€™t eat the same. By ignoring that slice of cake your dying for or you miss meals because you donâ€™t see yourself as beautiful. And it stresses me because we all have beauty and we should have the freedom to eat what we want to, as long as itâ€™s not damaging your health.

The media has possessed our younger selves that the only way we can be pretty is to be incredibly skinny.

I think we should have the choice to decide for ourselves what is gorgeous about our bodies. Its not a choice for the media, or anyone else for that matter. 
As always, Bridgey x

text:
Bella Thorne Rips Whoopi Goldberg For Shaming Nude Photos on â€˜The Viewâ€™

 Whoopi
Bella Thorne 'Shame On You, Whoopi!!!' For Shaming My Nude Pics 6/18/2019 3:19 PM PDT Bella Thorne is firing back at Whoopi Goldberg after she seemingly shamed Bella for having nude photos on her phone, on the cloud, or anywhere. In a series of super emotional posts Tuesday, Bella tearfully blasted Whoopi ... who took the stance on "The View" that celebs who take nude photos are just asking for trouble with hackers and, essentially, said they should know better.Â  Bella said Whoopi's comment only inflames a painful situation. She also suggested Whoopi's lack of sympathy toward young people who get exposed this way is part of the reason people commit suicide after their nudes are leaked. In case you missed it ... Bella's Twitter was hacked last week, and over the weekend she posted a series of topless photos in order to beat her alleged hacker to the punch. She says the person was attempting to extort her with the racy pics.Â  Whoopi, Meghan McCain, Sunny Hostin and Joy BeharÂ debated the issue in Monday's episode of "The View" ... and their convo clearly triggered Bella.Â  Bella says she's not going on "The View" anymore, because she doesn't want to be judged by a bunch of older women ... and she's calling out the hosts for brainwashing the next generation and accusing them of some serious double standards. text:
There is NO  Love in  Shaming... ğŸ’”

I was born and raised up in South Texas... my mind recalls memories of hearing older people's scorn as, "shame on you!" ...for Whatever, and to Whomever, I am unsure. I just remember that being a fairly common phraseology for chastisement down here. And it made sense, most of the time.

As an adult, I came across the works of my cousin (in Jest, for the name is the same ğŸ˜œ no direct relation, that I'm aware of) Dr. Brene Brown, whose monumental Work on studying the effects of  Shame have revealed to me what a major component of relational disfunction the carrying of Shame can become... my family, the alcoholics and otherwise, were frequent users of Sarcasm as Humor. It never occurred to me that such banter could strengthen One's inner sense of Shame, until I was in my late 40's... ğŸ’”

I now feel that, while an occasional quip or pun might be fun, I have ZERo desire or intentions of participating in anything that can cause another person to feel "less than", or shameful... we are all of the same Maker. He made NO junk! (another Southern expression, y'all ğŸ˜‡) so I pray that anyone dealing with current or residual Shame thoughts, feelings, identity traits, or other such negative manifestations of  awaken to  theTruth!

You, (yes YOU!) are a  ChildOfGod , gloriously  created in His image. ğŸ’ There is NO place for the carrying of any negative labels or condemnations...  awaken and  arise in  ChristConsciousness awareness, that YOU are a son or daughter of the King of kings, and that YOU were made for a very special and unique  Purpose! It wasn't to waste away your life in alcoholic delusions, or depressive anxiety and  Worry... you have a unique and special kinda Love within you. It will awaken through focused  prayer and  Understanding of God's Law... ğŸ’

Love Him. Love Self. Love Neighbors... May His greatest Blessings of Love, Grace, Mercy, and Peace leave you filled with Awe and Wonder, replacing all shame, guilt, and Anger, for those are the Lies (and favorite Tools) of the

text:
In South Asian culture, women are often made to "sit out" in the corner of a home and remain untouched during their periods. We're prevented from going to mosques and temples, and shamed for a natural part of life. The three of us grew up in Hindu homes with very different expectations during our time of the month. In this episode, we're going to explore why we aren't allowed to do those things, rant a little about how we aren't dirty or impure because we're on our period, and talk about how a biological process that is empowering and allows us to bring a life into the world has been shamed, hidden and awkwardly approached in South Asian culture, and how Western and Eastern menstrual equity are very, very different concepts. The new episode of  TWD is out! We're looking forward to hearing what you have to say.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

When I put up a Facebook status for this feature, Parthiv reached out to me in my inbox. 
He told me how he was always judged and made fun of for being skinny. He felt if he told his story, it could help people who were facing similar issues, and I couldnâ€™t have agreed more. Â° Â° Â°

One of the things that Parthiv said mirrored my ideas and why I started this feature in the first place. He said â€œBeing skinny or fat is not a crime. It is subjective. Everyone has an opinion and you will find people who will comment or bully you everywhere. There is no escaping it. It can get really tough especially when these people are your relatives and give you unsolicited advice that will make no sense.â€ The trick according to him is to accept yourself. â€œYou were born fabulousâ€ he exclaims. text: If you try to make someone do something, you will crush them with expectations. Not even God does that. People need to decide for themselves what to do, without coercion or shaming or manipulation, or else theyâ€™re only doing it to get you quiet. They wonâ€™t ever know why, and it will never become a part of them. Making demands is an external apparatus that will chokehold the people you claim to love. But if you truly love them, by listening and investing and sharing and even liking them, this is the only sort of love that will tenderize a heart to seek better for itself. To shame is to lay down bricks to make a shape, but without a soul. To show grace will take longer, but itâ€™s to plant a seed that pushes through the dirt into the air, towards a life that can breathe on its own. This is true empowerment.

comment_1: Grace + boundaries. Instead of forcing change through shaming or demanding, let the person know your boundaries. â€œIn order to protect my peace and sanity, if you continue to do x that hurts me profoundly without changing then I will have to remove myself from this relationship/situation.â€ Grace is so important, but grace without boundaries will get you hurt over and over. Demands donâ€™t work, but letting people know your boundaries and that they cannot expect you to just take being hurt over and over gracefully works.

text:
Yes,  Pride is now a celebration. A  celebration that grew from a  riot. A riot that grew from years of  anguish, fear, secrecy,  shaming, and eventually  resistance. Years of solitude and familial  abandonment, of arrests and police brutality, of bigotry and  hatecrimes... sound familiar? True, in so many ways we are not so evolved. In many communities globally it is still illegal to exist in oneâ€™s queerness. Folks can still be fired from their careers for loving their partner. Or worse, â€œarrestedâ€ and then disappeared. Today. This is still happening today. 
So while Pride is a celebration of the liberties many of us are fortunate to now enjoy, let us be mindful. Let us remember that if some of us are not free, none of us are free. Let us remember that these freedoms we have in  California can vanish tomorrow, and are not consistently true in these â€œUnitedâ€ States. [not to mention the ugly that still exists even in this left-coast state despite our progressive efforts]
Let us remember that the patriarchal, heteronormative,  capitalists seek to gain in vain - pushing their  rainbow swag to fool you into believing they support  LGBTQ+ issues. Do your  research before spending your  vote on how we continue forward. Better yet, spend your money on supporting  QTPOC owned businesses,  entrepreneurs, etc! Let our choices remind our communities that we  support each other and that weâ€™re here alllll year long, not just in June during  pridemonth. Let our choices bridge the months between Black History month, Pride month, and Latin@ heritage month (among other holidays) to speak to the  intersections of our  identities not being pigeonholed. So yes, let us stand  proud, today and every day, and let us truly  honor those on whoâ€™s shoulders we stand. â€¢â€¢â€¢ Swipe to see a few of my favorite  qtpoc folks doing amazing work, give â€˜em a follow, support their work, cheer them on! :)

text:
No one taught me what to do with my feelings as a  highlysensitivechild : how to manage and regulate my emotional states exacerbated by living in a chaotic unpredictable home. Iâ€™m pretty sure Iâ€™m still learning how to do it. ğŸ˜‚
.
In fact my childhood was rife with mixed messages and a great deal of  minimizing and  shaming. .
.
I suppose itâ€™s no surprise that my turning-5-on-Tuesday ! boy is incredibly sensitive, extremely creative and theatrical and exceedingly intense. I repeat, not mellow. Emotionally that is. Parenting him, itâ€™s demanding to understate it. Heâ€™s also incredibly cuddly, very funny, and highly bright and imaginative. Oh and strong. So Stroong.
.
We made these charts this morning in a bit of a rush when I realized how long overdue it is to have a visual, concrete conversation about what to do when weâ€™re furious and deeply upset. .
.
I realized I hadnâ€™t been giving him clear enough guidance and protocols for how to self-regulate. He gets just apoplectic when clothes arenâ€™t right, sleeves donâ€™t match in length or basically whenever he doesnâ€™t get his way. He screams so loudly I worry a neighbor will call the cops ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜­ flails, hits, kicks (just Chris and me, heâ€™s a angel with everyone else) and just has nuclear meltdowns on the reg. I have to make sure heâ€™s not  hangry too and give him enough fat and protein.
.
I donâ€™t do well with this behavior as a survivor of childhood abuse. I lose it more often than Iâ€™d like. Screaming and hitting are a huge trigger. Oof.  gettingtriggeredbyourchildren how is that not a hashtag? .
.
As a parents  of little ones we are charged with regulating ourselves AND our kids. Thank goodness I grew up with  emotionalliteracy 
Ideally we as parents model healthy coping skills. (As opposed to a lot of cursing under our breath and emotional eating)
How gratifying to watch him show chris and his friend how to  crocodilebreath and  windbreath  Some of these tools I made up, some are based on what Iâ€™ve learned about the nervous system and some Iâ€™ve collected from others. ğŸ™ğŸ½

text: I recently saw a post by one of my mentors about the Body Acceptance Challenge that really hit home with me. So often when im around friends i feel uncomfortable by their comments towards me about my body or what I eat. "Jordan eat a burger will ya." We need to accept all body types. Skinny, heart shaped, freckled, big boobed, etc. Every body is different. I work hard to feel comfortable to be in this skin. To have a healthy body so that i can chase my boys around. Dont shame those who are doing the same. Lets praise those who are putting in the work to be the best versions of themselves. Were all the same at the heart of it. We all have rolls when we sit down. We all have cellulite. We all have that one body part that we scrutinize more than any other body part. Lets change how we talk to each other and lift each other up. Our bodies are beautiful things that can do amazing things and they come in all shapes and sizes.

text:
GUNDU KATTU SIRRIKI

It is not necessary for you to have a picture perfect face or body to be infront of the camera! You just have to be YOU, be CONFIDENT, be DAUNTLESS!! I am pretty sure that everyone is facing body shaming nowadays! So this what I pretty hear almost everytime! " hey, you put on weight dy la" ;"your face so chubby dy" "your thighs are so big, dont wear shorts" !! I am so done with all these statements or comments towards my body size or shape! Okay I was thin and I put on weight !! Its my body of course I know that I put on weight ! Body shaming is not for those who are fat or chubby, but also for those who are thin. Those who are thin also going through body shaming. "You're so thin, do you even eat?" "You dont have boobs or ass, not nice la your body shape"! What the fuck is wrong with this society man ?! Like seriously, fat also problem, thin also problem; so you people expect all the 7.7 billion human being in this world to be in perfect size???? Body-shaming manifests in many ways:

1)Â Criticizing your own appearance, through a judgment or comparison to another person. (eg: â€œIâ€™m so ugly compared to her.â€ â€œLook at how broad my shoulders are.â€) 2)Â Criticizing anotherâ€™s appearance in front of them, (eg: â€œWith those thighs, the short dress ain't gonna look nice on you .â€) 3)Â Criticizing anotherâ€™s appearance without their knowledge. (eg: â€œDid you see what sheâ€™s wearing today? Not flattering.â€) When the photographers approached me to do this photoshoot they asked me to wear sleeveless blouse, when I heard that I hesitated for a bit! Because I do have broad shoulders, fat arms which not flattering at all! But one thing I asked myself was IF NOT NOW, THEN WHEN? So I said okay to this concept and did the shoot!! I'm so proud of myself that I stopped doubting on myself and my body!

text:
After drastically losing 10 kgs within a span of a month, due to some health and mental sickness, here's what I have realised -
1. Body shaming happens to skinny people too.
2. It is very hard to gain weight.
3. When you are used to well fitted clothes, and suddenly nothing fits, it hurts.
4. Just as a person trying to lose weight, who's not happy with their body, we skinny people too get frustrated trying to do the opposite. 
5. Self love is awesome. No matter what body shape you have, embrace the beautiful creation that you are. Stay healthy and flaunt your body, however it is. Loving thyself is great! Ignoring all the negativity, have fun, eat whatever you wish. â¤
But everyone has a certain wish, make that happen for yourself and yourself only. Other's & negativity are not worth it. .

text:
Too fat, too skinny, too muscular, too something... I recently had a family member remark that I was "sooo skinny" (and not in a good way, as if that ever is). As someone who has been skinny, soft, skinny/fat (that's a thing people ğŸ¤¦), pregnant, lost the baby weight then gained it back, there is nothing more frustrating than having someone criticize your weight. 
My response to this person was that my body was not theirs to observe and have an opinion on. Whether I choose to "let myself go a little" or hit the gym hard, has nothing to do with you. It's a reflection of where I am in my life and the priorities I have. 
It doesn't matter what you look like, someone will always have something to say. Oh and shaping your body to please everyone is absolutely impossible. I am the fittest I have ever been and someone's interpretation of that is that I'm too skinny. Others will say I'm too muscular and to lighten up on those weights before I look too masculine (yes I have also gotten that feedback). My diet is far from perfect. My gym routine is not always consistent. And I like wineğŸ·. If you like how I look, cool. If not, look past. I'm on a mission of becoming the best version of myself in all areas of my life and those who try to slow me down will get left behind.

text:
Negative comments about one's appearance can come from anyone, including well-meaning family members.
Academic studies and research indicate that we live in an image-heavy society online and in person. We see the promotion of an 'ideal body' in advertisements, magazines, newspapers, billboards, shopping windows, etc. 
Weight stigma which is a negative response to someone based on their weight, is the fourth most common form of social discrimination amongst adults. It is the only form of discrimination which is still widely deemed to be socially acceptable.
We claim ourselves to be a modern and progressive society, yet we continue to judge and discriminate. 
Body shaming has a direct impact on the mental health of people, and makes them dissatisfied and unhappy.

I really wanted to post this picture and share something that always conflicts me from within about our time.....
This is me, 6 years ago.... I had just joined my engineering college and was a part of a metal band as a drummer and for a really long time...i wished to grow my hair long and when i reached in college, i chose to grow them then..... it took me almost 2 years to grow them to the longest they were(unfortunately I donâ€™t have a picture of that day). I took immense care of them, researched, applied products to make them the way i wanted my hair to be..and when they did grow, i was very happy!
Now when i talk about the society in general and the society in which i enlist myself (coz everyone is part of a society), some loved my hair and some thought i was foolish to do what i did not just my hair but to â€œmyselfâ€ and let me be clear these were and are some of the closest people around me and i still love and will always do....but to be honest this was a straight forward case of body shaming (please donâ€™t take this in the wrong way). But i never felt bad about being subjected to such criticism for what i chose to do. And recently I realised the reason for that coz i just decided to grow them back again and i once again heard a lot of opinion. The reason was â€œme and my awareness which taught me not only to believe in what i believe, but also to differentiate between a comment which  is just a comment and a statement made deliberately to body shame meâ€, and i would like to share the same with everyone!! â€œThe first person who needs to be comfortable and accept what they are or what they wanna be is the first hand concerned individual itself!! PERIOD!!â€ And after that you not only see the statements turning into compliments but also the inner belief and the growth of self respect one starts to feel for themselves....
SO PEOPLE!! JUST OWN IT!! If youâ€™re hairy and wanna be clean shaved, OWN IT!! If youâ€™re â€œFATâ€ and you love being â€œFATâ€, OWN IT!! Love yourself..â™¥ï¸

My six year old was â€œmaking a girl prettyâ€ by removing her freckles/skin blemishes, adding eye lashes... and then broke out a SCALPEL to fix her nose. What in the ever loving god was that?!? I grabbed the iPad the moment the scalpel came out. Turns out an ad banner with other games appeared on the page (Iâ€™m seriously hoping the school has firewalls preventing these), and my kid innocently clicked on what just looked like more games. Seriously, though, this is where it starts. Who is making and marketing these games to preschoolers?!? Not only are kids bombarded with this stuff on tv, etc, games are being pushed where â€œimperfectionsâ€ are fixed with scalpels. Iâ€™m glad we were watching, but this is just another reminder to pay attention and talk to children about beauty - it comes in all shapes, sizes, colours, and more. Work with your kids to actively oppose body shaming. ALL bodies are worthy of love and kindness.
.
.

text:
I've always been thin. I'd never experienced being fat. Yet, I know how being fat feels like. Because the society we live in now is full of judgmental people. 
I've been called 'teeli', 'chipkali', 'lakri', 'hadiyon ka dhaancha', 'sukhi chiri' and much more I can't remember rn. And it hurts... It really DOES! .
My sister/friend who's a lil' fat has been called 'bhens', 'moti', and blah blah (sometimes by my ownself). And ik she must feel bad when people(including me) call her with those names! .
I think fat people can be encouraged to do exercise or join gym or else just walk after meals. Thus, they can make themselves smart and healthy in some ways. 
But us, thin people, we can't do anything. I sometimes eat a lot. Not at home but at school. But its just that ke wo khana kahin lagta nahi hai! Its not our fault. Its how our bodies work. .
Just stop making us feel bad about ourselves. Please! STOP THIS BODY SHAMING. Specially these khaandaan ki aunties whom we are not even free with (Ik they can't read this post), they make us/me feel worse. Idk why but still. These aunties need to stop. The people whom we interact with after a whole year and they comeup with, 'Ohhh... Aik saal me kitni moti/patli ho gai ho.',they need to stop. .
I think the society need to change their mindsets . This post to all those who are being called bhen/machis ki teeli in their dailylife. You people know how it feels to be called with these names. So, don't call others like that. Act like human. Live like human! 
And I'm really sorry to all those whom I ever called like that! You people are really beautiful! ğŸ’•

text:
On  bodyshaming

I suffered deep emotional hurts from people calling me out on my scanty (light) hair. This had a huge negative impact on my self-esteem. I remember there was a time I couldn't leave my house wearing just my hair (as a secondary school student). If it wasn't threaded or braided with attachment, I would tie a bandana to cover it. .
.
The shame and helplessness I felt then in my life was something else.
.
.
I love my hair today - still scanty, but hey, I'm not perfect, and frankly, I don't need to be (God made my hair this way).
.
.
Note to adults (parents, aunts/uncles, big sis/bro, teachers etc.): Do not tease a child with their physical challenges ("playfully", "jokingly" or otherwise). You are damaging his/her self-esteem each time you do. You're basically saying to the child: "you are not good enough". Because the mind is highly impressionable (esp. that of kids), the child will believe you. Stop raising timid children. Stop body shaming ANYONE.
.
.
Have you been body-shamed before? How did that make you feel? .
.
.
.

Reblog reads: â€œAs someone who has been â€œthin-shamedâ€ I can say it does Not at all go hand in hand with fat shaming. People â€œthin-shamingâ€ me was mostly verbal harassment- youâ€™re too skinny, you look like a boy, eat a fucking cheeseburger, whatâ€™s wrong with you why donâ€™t you like food?
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
But guess what, I donâ€™t have a problem finding clothes that fit me. There arenâ€™t companies that refuse to make clothes for my size. There is no shortage of messages telling me that despite the harassment of some, I am still beautiful and ideal even if Iâ€™m unhealthy. Despite being thin-shamed, I still PANICKED when I started a medicine that made me gain weight, and I had to really analyze that, because no matter what my culture will still say that â€œfat is unidealâ€ â€œfat is badâ€ and â€œhonestly its fine to starve yourself / but shameful and bad to overeat.â€ â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
So â€œthin-shamingâ€ is shitty because itâ€™s shitty to be judged and have people make assumptions about you. But Fat-shaming is institutional, itâ€™s not just individuals harassment and judgement, itâ€™s potential jobs, itâ€™s clothing companies, itâ€™s media and advertisement, all telling you youâ€™re bad as you are. Like what a way shittier thing.

text:
The mom who is thin. Can we talk about thin privilege? What is it? From what Iâ€™ve researched and listened to from other bloggers it is essentially the luxury of not having to deal with fat shaming. There is so much that goes a long with that of course. Basically I donâ€™t have people groan or roll their eyes when they sit next to me on a plane, I can shop at any store Iâ€™d like, I donâ€™t get ugly looks when I eat a pizza, my bathing suit choice isnâ€™t judged at the pool, and I would probably go as far as saying I get better customer service because of my size as well. All of that is a privilege because of my size. I could be the biggest jerk, and still all of the above applies. If you think this isnâ€™t a thing look around next time youâ€™re at the store, on the subway, in a line at McDonaldâ€™s. Open your eyes and truly look at your sisters all around you. I can sit here and tell a size 12+ woman sheâ€™s gorgeous all day, but my opinion comes with an emptiness and a lack of empathy. I want to be on the right side of this body positive movement that Iâ€™ve been following through accounts such as @thegarciadiaries and @thebirdspapaya and I want to genuinely spread love and acceptance but I am a mom who is thin, and while I still struggle with every roll or stretch mark I have, I realize that my body is what society deems acceptable. There was a time when curves and a little junk in the trunk is what was sold as Sexy. Marilyn Monroe is proof of that. What happened? When did it change? How can I as a thin women, use my influence in this movement without coming across as naive? @mingey recently said â€œINFLUENCE = POWER. And if youâ€™re taking advantage of that- EMPOWER.â€ .
.
.
.

TOPIC  38; Wimbledon Fashion, Seating, Appearance, ETC. 
Straight to it, shall we? 
1. WHY IS PIPPA ALSO IN THE ROYAL BOX? 
According to the official Wimbledon website, the Royal Box is used for friends and guests of Wimbledon, which includes "British and overseas royal families, heads of government, people from the world of tennis, commercial partners, British Armed Forces, prominent media organisations, supporters of tennis and other walks of life". This means that IF the GUESTS of Wimbledon have in turned invited you to come along, like Pippa has YEARS ago, they are allowed to turn out. If not, it would have to be by invitation of the President of Wimbledon. 
2. KATES APPEARANCE - Kate's dress was last worn in 2016, this is a repeat. I'm not sure WHAT the issue is with the fit, and WHAT the issue IS with wearing clothes that have similar fit and flare, or patterns or Colours. It's not you who is wearing the dress. 
Here are some PSYCHOLOGICAL REASONS behind why women sometimes gravitate towards a certain style OR "work uniforms". - we instinctively gravitate towards the clothes that originally made us feel great, safe and secure. Especially in this harsh world of a royal, where EVERYONE is thinking their opinions are the ONLY correct one, it is hard not to be affected. As such, we tend to hold on to the things that remind us of happier times of which could manifest in our fashion choices. - People tend to wear things that they LIKE and have found to suit their body shape. As with all happy memories, the endorphins that come with finding something that SUITS YOUR body shape and YOU, tends to stick with you. The comfort and confidence that comes with often leads people to buying things in a certain way. - Kate seems to be the "classic fashion type". This means A) Investment in clothing to be reworn over YEARS, B) sticking to classic lines, things that suit her, C) Basically, the clothes have proven to be a HIT. So that means less criticisms, more focus on her patronages, as well as acting as a "work uniform". Frankly, it's easier to stick to something than try something new all the time. There's no pressure to change her fashion choices, very frankly

text:
Dear Body, 
I am sorry for not treating you the way you should be treated. I apologize for accepting all the comments on you thrown by the society. When the society was screaming, 'Skinny' constantly, I believed it. I am sorry that I accepted so many lies about you. I want you to know it wasn't me who hated you but the society constantly pressurizing me to hate you and fit into something called 'Perfect'
You've been a home to my soul for the past 24 years and I'm grateful for all that you've done so far. I love you for being so Flawless. 
I promise you, I'll not let other people's opinions upset me because at the end it's my opinion that counts. You are my business and nobody's else. You are my body. I will care for you and provide you with all the nourishment that you need. You are a tiny universe and I am not going to fit you into the mold of unattainable acceptability defined by the society. 
You are a recovering warrior. I will trust you and treasure youğŸ–¤
